Seasonal ARIMA

The SARIMA models, or ARIMA\((p,d,q)(P,D,Q)_m\), an enhancement of ARIMA models to handle time series with seasonality.

\[\begin{equation} \begin{array}{c c} (p, d, q) & (P, D, Q)_m\\ {\uparrow} & {\uparrow}\\ \text{Non-seasonal} & \text{Seasonal}\\ \end{array} \end{equation}\]

where:

  • \(m\) is the length of the seasonal period (the number of observations in one year).
  • \(d\) is the number of lag-1 differences
  • \(p\) is the number of ordinary AR lags (\(x_{t-1}, x_{t-2}, ..., x_{t-p}\))
  • \(q\) is the number of ordinary MA lags (\(w_{t-1}, w_{t-2}, ..., w_{t-q}\))
  • \(D\) is the number of seasonal differences
  • \(P\) is the number of seasonal AR lags: (\(x_{t-m}, x_{t-2m}, ..., x_{t-Pm}\))
  • \(Q\) is the number of seasonal MA lags: (\(w_{t-m}, w_{t-2m}, ..., w_{t-Qm}\))

The seasona part of the model consists of terms that are similar to the non-seasonal cimponents of the model, but involve backshifts of the seasonal period.

The model combines the seasonal and non-seasonal parts of the model in a multiplicative manner. The resulting model can thefefore be quite complex to write down and is non-linear. In terms of the backshift operator the model looks as follows:

\[\begin{equation} \begin{array}{c c c c c c} (1-\phi_1B - \cdots - \phi_p B^p) & (1-\Phi_1B^m - \cdots - \Phi_p B^{Pm}) & (1-B)^d & (1-B^m)^D x_{t} & = (1 + \theta_1 B + \cdots + \theta_q B^q) & (1 + \Theta_1 B^m + \cdots + \Theta_q B^{Qm})w_t\\ {\uparrow} & {\uparrow} & {\uparrow} & {\uparrow} & {\uparrow} &{\uparrow}\\ \text{AR($p$)} & \text{AR($P$)} & \text{$d$ differences} & \text{$D$ differences} & \text{MA($q$)} & \text{MA($Q$)}\\ \end{array} \end{equation}\]

Example: an ARIMA \((1,1,1)(1,1,1)_4\) model without a constant for quarterly data (\(m=4\)) and can be written as:

\[ (1 - \phi_{1}B)~(1 - \Phi_{1}B^{4}) (1 - B) (1 - B^{4})y_{t} = (1 + \theta_{1}B)~ (1 + \Theta_{1}B^{4})\varepsilon_{t} \] Example: an ARIMA \((2,2,1)(1,2,2)_4\) model with a constant for quarterly data (\(m=4\)) and can be written as:

\[ (1 - \phi_{1}B - \phi_2B^2)~(1 - \Phi_{1}B^{4}) (1 - B)^2 (1 - B^{4})^2y_{t} = c+ (1 + \theta_{1}B)~ (1 + \Theta_{1}B^{4} + \Theta_{2}B^{8})\varepsilon_{t} \]

ACF and PACF of a Seasonal Arima Model

The PACF and ACF of a purely seasonal model AR or MA model will exhibit spikes in the seasonal lags (lags \(m, 2m, 3m\dots\)) following the same cut-off and tail-off logic of non-seasonal models. In this case the associated table to determine the seasonal lags would be:

sAR(P) (Q=0) sMA(Q) (P=0) sARMA(P,Q)
ACF (seasonal lags) Tails-off Cuts off after seasonal lag Q Tails-off
PACF (seasonal lags) Cuts-off after seasonal lag P Tails off Tails-off

In the table above note the fact that we now have \(P\) and \(Q\) instead of \(p\) and \(q\) because we are referring to the seasonal part of the ARIMA model. Note as well that now we have sAR instead of AR indicating seasonal auto-regressive model and sMA indicating seasonal moving-average model.

Regarding the expression seasonal lag: * The first seasonal lag would be lag 4 for quarterly data, lag 12 for monthly data, etcâ¦ * The second seasonal lag would be lag 8 for quarterly data, lag 24 for monthly data, etcâ¦

After rendering the data trend-stationary and seasonal-stationary by means of seasonal differences (\(D\)) and ordinary differences (\(d\)), we would print the ACF and PACF of the resulting stationary series and then use the table above to interpret the seasonal part of the model looking at the seasonal lags of the ACF and PACF.

For the non-seasonal part of the model we have to use the table introduced in the session on ARMA models:

AR(p) (q=0) MA(q) (p=0) ARMA(p,q)
ACF (non-seasonal lags) Tails-off Cuts off after lag q Tails-off
PACF (non-seasonal lags) Cuts-off after lag p Tails off Tails-off

All of this is better understood through examples.

Examples with simulated data (purely seasonal models):

Again we are going to start with simulated data to see how the seasonal lags of the ACF and PACF of purely sMA (seasonal MA) and sAR (seasonal AR) models look like:

Example: ARIMA\((0,0,0)(1,0,0)_{12}\)

set.seed(1011)
y_sar1 <- sarima.sim(sar=c(0.75), S=12) %>% as_tsibble()
y_sar1 %>% autoplot()
Plot variable not specified, automatically selected `.vars = value`

y_sar1 %>% 
  gg_tsdisplay(value, plot_type='partial', lag=48)

In this case the seasonal lags of the ACF tail off and the seasonal lags of the PACF cut-off after the first seasonal lag (lag 12). Therefore \(P=1\) and \(Q=0\)

Example: ARIMA\((0,0,0)(2,0,0)_{12}\)

set.seed(1011)
y_sar2 <- sarima.sim(sar=c(0.75, -0.6), S=12) %>% as_tsibble()
y_sar2 %>% autoplot()
Plot variable not specified, automatically selected `.vars = value`

y_sar2 %>% 
  gg_tsdisplay(value, plot_type='partial', lag=48)

In this case the seasonal lags of the ACF tail off and the seasonal lags of the PACF cut-off after the second seasonal lag (lag 12). Therefore \(P=2\) and \(Q=0\)

Example: another ARIMA\((0,0,0)(2,0,0)_{12}\)

This example is picked up to show that the resulting ACF and PACF can be confusing

set.seed(1011)
y_sar2_alt <- sarima.sim(sar=c(0.75, -0.25), S=12) %>% as_tsibble()
y_sar2_alt %>% autoplot()
Plot variable not specified, automatically selected `.vars = value`

y_sar2_alt %>% 
  gg_tsdisplay(value, plot_type='partial', lag=48)

In this case if we knew nothing about the data we could perfectly think that both ACF and PACF are cutting-off. We will proceed as indicated in the notebook for ARMA models, that is, we will fit two models:

  • Model 1: model hinted by the PACF
    • Cut-off of PACF at the second seasonal lag
    • Assumtion that ACF is tailing-off
    • Result: \(P=2\) and \(Q=0\) (ARIMA(0,0,0)(2,0,0)12)
  • Model 2: model hinted by the PACF
    • Cut-off of ACF at the second seasonal lag
    • Assumtion that PACF is tailing-off
    • Result: \(P=0\) and \(Q=2\) (ARIMA(0,0,0)(0,0,2)12)

The example goes to show that even for data that should be quite clean and clear (simulated data), the ACF and PACF can be confusing.

Examples with real data

The important thing when interpreting ACF and PACF now is to separate between the seasonal and the non-seasonal parts of the model.

US Unemployment in leisure and hospitality

US unemployment data for leisure and hospitality jobs from Jan 2001 to Sept 2019

leisure <- us_employment %>%
  filter(Title == "Leisure and Hospitality",
         year(Month) > 2000) %>%
  mutate(
          Employed = Employed/1000,
          # First seasonal difference
          emp_sdiff = difference(Employed, 12),
          # First order difference
          emp_sdiff_diff = difference(emp_sdiff, 1)         
         ) %>%
  select(Month, Employed, emp_sdiff, emp_sdiff_diff)

autoplot(leisure, Employed) +
  labs(title = "US employment: leisure and hospitality",
       y="Number of people (millions)")

leisure %>%
  gg_tsdisplay(emp_sdiff,
               plot_type='partial', lag=36) +
  labs(title="Seasonally differenced", y="")
Warning: Removed 12 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).
Warning: Removed 12 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

The ACF of the series after one seasonal lag clearly exhibits non-stationarity in the trend, so we take now first-order differences

leisure %>%
  gg_tsdisplay(emp_sdiff_diff,
               plot_type='partial', lag=48) +
  labs(title="Seasonally differenced", y="")
Warning: Removed 13 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).
Warning: Removed 13 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Now the series looks stationary (we could perform a KPSS test to check this).

The important thing when interpreting ACF and PACF now is to separate between the seasonal and the non-seasonal part of the model:

  • Non-seasonal part of the model: both seem to cut-off. Therefore we have two alternatives, each hitned by the cut-off of the ACF and the PACF
    • ACF cut-off seems to signal an MA2 model (\(q=2\))
    • PACF cut-off seems to signal an AR2 model (\(p=2\))
  • Seasonal part of the model:
    • PACF tails-off
    • ACF cut-off seems to signal an Seasonal MA1 model.
    • The combination of these two patterns suggest (\(Q=1\))

We therefore propose two models combining the alternatives obtained for the non-seasonal and the seasonal parts of the model and taking into account that \(d=1\) and \(D=1\) since we have taken one seasonal difference and one first-order difference:

  • ARIMA\((2,1,0)(0,1,1)_{12}\)
  • ARIMA\((0,1,2)(0,1,1)_{12}\)

We will also include an automatically fitted model, with stepwise=FALSE and approximation=FALSE so that the search is as thorough as possible:

# Note the amount of time required for automatically fitting an ARIMA model
# if the search is performed in this thorough manner

# Since there is only one series to model, this is no problem.
fit <- leisure %>%
  model(
    arima012011 = ARIMA(Employed ~ pdq(0,1,2) + PDQ(0,1,1)),
    arima210011 = ARIMA(Employed ~ pdq(2,1,0) + PDQ(0,1,1)),
    auto = ARIMA(Employed, stepwise = FALSE, approx = FALSE)
  )
fit %>% pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "Model name",
                     values_to = "Orders")
# A mable: 3 x 2
# Key:     Model name [3]
  `Model name`                    Orders
  <chr>                          <model>
1 arima012011  <ARIMA(0,1,2)(0,1,1)[12]>
2 arima210011  <ARIMA(2,1,0)(0,1,1)[12]>
3 auto         <ARIMA(2,1,0)(1,1,1)[12]>
glance(fit) %>% arrange(AICc) %>% select(.model:BIC)
# A tibble: 3 Ã 6
  .model       sigma2 log_lik   AIC  AICc   BIC
  <chr>         <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
1 auto        0.00142    395. -780. -780. -763.
2 arima210011 0.00145    392. -776. -776. -763.
3 arima012011 0.00146    391. -775. -775. -761.

ARIMA() uses unitroot_nsdiffs() and unotroot_diffs() to determine \(d\) (number of ordinary differences) and \(D\) (number of seasonal differences). The other podel orders (\(p\), \(q\), \(P\) and \(Q\)) are determines as before by minimizing AICc.

The three models have similar AICc values, with the automatically fitted model slightly beating the other two. Let us inspect the residuals for this best model:

fit %>% select(auto) %>% gg_tsresiduals(lag=36)

n_params <- fit %>% select(auto) %>% tidy() %>% nrow()
augment(fit) %>%
  filter(.model == "auto") %>%
  # Lag 24 = 2*m
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag=24, dof=4)
# A tibble: 1 Ã 3
  .model lb_stat lb_pvalue
  <chr>    <dbl>     <dbl>
1 auto      16.6     0.680

The high p-value indicates that we fail to reject the null, that is, we the hypothesis that the residuals are in fact white noise.

We now have a seasonal ARIMA model that has been selected based on AICc and passes the residuals test. It is ready for forecasting:

forecast(fit, h=36) %>%
  filter(.model=='auto') %>%
  autoplot(leisure) +
  labs(title = "US employment: leisure and hospitality",
       y="Number of people (millions)")

  • Seasonal pattern captured well
  • Increasing trend extends the recent pattern. The trend is induced by the double differencing.

Corticosteroid drug sales in australia

H02 drugs under the Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical classification scheme:

h02 <- PBS %>%
  filter(ATC2 == "H02") %>%
  summarise(Cost = sum(Cost)/1e6)

h02 %>%
  mutate(log(Cost)) %>%
  pivot_longer(-Month) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Month, y = value)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(name ~ ., scales = "free_y") +
  labs(y="", title="Corticosteroid drug scripts (H02)")

Have this chart in mind to follow the steps necessary to fit an ARIMA model:

Logarithmic transformation to stabilize the increasing variance with the series.

After this there is strong seasonality and obvious trend non-stationarity.

We will take differences to do away with these two features

h02 <-
  h02 %>% 
  mutate(
    sdiff_logcost = difference(log(Cost), 12),
    sdiff_diff_logcost = difference(sdiff_logcost, 1)
  )
h02 %>% gg_tsdisplay(sdiff_logcost,
                     plot_type='partial', lag_max = 36)
Warning: Removed 12 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).
Warning: Removed 12 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Look at the last few observations. They look different from the rest. This migt be because data are sometimes revised when earlier sales are reported late (that is, data might still need to be consolidated).

The ACF of this signal clearly exhibits signs of non-stationarity. It is not clear whether another difference should be taken or not. Looking at a formal test, it looks like another difference should be taken. However many analysts may look at the simply seasonally differenced data and find it is stationary enough despite the statistical test (there is always a certain degree of subjectivity in the analysis). Consequently we will analyze both cases and compare results.

For the data subject to only one seasonal difference \(d=0, D=1\):

  • Non-seasonal part:
    • PACF signals AR(3) (cot-off at lag 3)
    • ACF tails-off
  • Seasonal part:
    • PACF signals Seasonal AR(2) (cut-off at second seasonal lag)
    • ACF is not indicative of any simple model (no significant seasonal lags)

Therefore here we will propose ARIMA\((3,0,0)(2,1,0)_12\)

For the data subject to both ordinary and seasonal differences (\(d=1, D=1\)):

h02 %>% gg_tsdisplay(sdiff_diff_logcost,
                     plot_type='partial', lag_max = 48)
Warning: Removed 13 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).
Warning: Removed 13 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  • Non-seasonal part:
    • PACF seems to suggest AR(2) or AR(4)
    • ACF is tailing-off
  • Seasonal-part
    • ACF seems to suggest seasonal MA(2) (cut-off at second seasonal lag)
    • PACF seems to hint towards a seasonal AR(1) (although the significance of lag 12 is weak).

Therefore, some candidate models could be:

  • ARIMA\((2,1,0)(1,1,0)_{12}\)
  • ARIMA\((2,1,0)(0,1,2)_{12}\)

IMPORTANT NOTE ON ORDERS OF DIFFERENCING:

We have proposed models with \(d=0\) \(D=1\) and models with \(d=1\) \(D=1\).

Note that these models have different orders of differencing!, so a comparison between them in terms of AIC or other information criteria is not possible, because the data to which they have been fitted is different!! (their likelihood is different). We can only compare in terms of AIC models with the same order of differencing.

We will fit thes models along with:

  • An automatically fitted model with all ARIMA orders free.
  • An automatically fitted model for which we enforce the constraint \(d=0\) and \(D=1\).
  • An automatically fitted model for which we enforce the constraint \(d=1\) and \(D=1\).
fit <- 
  h02 %>%
    model(
      arima_300210 = ARIMA(log(Cost) ~ pdq(3,0,0) + PDQ(2,1,0)),
      arima_210012 = ARIMA(log(Cost) ~ pdq(2,1,0) + PDQ(0,1,2)),
      arima_210110 = ARIMA(log(Cost) ~ pdq(2,1,0) + PDQ(1,1,0)),
      auto = ARIMA(log(Cost), stepwise = FALSE, approx = FALSE),
      auto_d0_D1 = ARIMA(log(Cost) ~ pdq(d=0) + PDQ(D=1), stepwise = FALSE, approx = FALSE),
      auto_d1_D1 = ARIMA(log(Cost) ~ pdq(d=1) + PDQ(D=1), , stepwise = FALSE, approx = FALSE)
    )

Let us create a table to inspect the orders of the automatically fitted models along with those we fully specified (this is for the html output, in RStudio it is best to inspect the variable in the variable explorer)

Remember we can only compare the AIC between models with the same order of differencing. This is because differencing changes the data to which we are fitting the model.

Comparsion of models in terms of cross-validation

Let us now take the last four years as the size of our sallest training dataset and perform cross-validation to compare all these models.

To compare ARIMA models in terms of AIC, it is necessary that they all have the same order of differencing but for cross-validation this is not an issue.

train_smallest <- h02 %>% slice(1:(n()-4*12)) %>% nrow()

h02_cv <- h02 %>% stretch_tsibble(.init=train_smallest, .step = 2)

We now need to explicitly state every model, or else R will look for the best model for each training dataset!!. This does not make sense, since we want to compare the same models across all datasets, not fitting one dataset to each model.

fit_cv <- 
h02_cv %>% 
  model(
    arima_210012 = ARIMA(log(Cost) ~ pdq(2, 1, 0) + PDQ(0, 1, 2)),
    
    # Automatically fitted now explicitly specified:
    arima_213011 = ARIMA(log(Cost) ~ pdq(2, 1, 3) + PDQ(0, 1, 1)),
    
    arima_300210 = ARIMA(log(Cost) ~ pdq(3, 0, 0) + PDQ(2, 1, 0)),
    
    # Automatically fitted now explicitly specified:
    arima_301012 = ARIMA(log(Cost) ~ pdq(3, 0, 1) + PDQ(0, 1, 2))
  )
# We want to compute up to two years ahead
fc_cv <- 
  fit_cv %>% forecast(h=24)

The units of the RMSE are millions of $AUD (Australian dollars).

It appears that the models with both first and second order differences have a lower RMSE. Of these, the automatically selected model (which had a lower AIC than the one we picked up from the ACF and PACF graphs) seems to perform better in terms of RMSE.

This would therefore be a good model to pick among all those that we have fitted.

Finally we would fit this model to the totality of our data and perform forecasts:

h02 %>%
  model(ARIMA(log(Cost) ~ 0 + pdq(2,1,3) + PDQ(0,1,1))) %>%
  forecast() %>%
  autoplot(h02) +
  labs(y=" $AU (millions)",
       title="Corticosteroid drug scripts (H02) sales")
